
Header parsing is the only stage that discovers module-wide top-level declarations.
It parses top-level declaration shells so later stages don't reconstruct them from raw tokens.

Headers make AST linear.
That is the whole point.

## Main path

`src/compiler_frontend/headers/parse_file_headers.rs`

Related paths:

- `src/compiler_frontend/headers/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/declaration_syntax/`
- `src/compiler_frontend/headers/beandown_prepare.rs`
- `src/compiler_frontend/headers/plain_markdown_prepare.rs`

## What header parsing owns

Header parsing owns:

- import and re-export parsing
- facade-only `export` parsing and public/private facade metadata
- import path validation and normalization
- file-local import/visibility environment construction
- declaration shell parsing for constants, functions, structs, choices, type aliases, traits and conformance metadata
- top-level dependency edge generation
- start-body token separation
- top-level const fragment placement metadata
- source-kind preparation hooks that turn non-`.bst` inputs into ordinary headers

Header parsing doesn't type-check executable bodies or fold expressions.
It should store normalized, validated path/reference forms instead of raw import/path syntax when enough context exists.

## Dependency edges

Header dependency edges include every top-level declaration dependency needed before AST can resolve declarations linearly:

- imported declaration references
- type alias targets
- struct and choice field type annotations
- function parameter and return type annotations
- constant explicit type annotations
- fixed collection capacity references in type annotations when the capacity is a visible compile-time constant
- constant initializer references to other constants
- structurally exposed const-template condition/control references when header parsing can identify them without parsing full template body semantics

Executable function/start body references don't participate in dependency sorting.
Body-local declarations don't participate in dependency sorting.
The implicit entry start header is always appended last.

## Declaration shells

A declaration shell is structured top-level header data, not a resolved AST node.

Examples:

- constant shell: name, export flag, explicit type annotation, initializer token span/tokens, initializer reference hints and source order
- function shell: name, generic parameters, parsed signature and body tokens
- struct shell: name, generic parameters, parsed field names/types and default token data where applicable
- choice shell: name, generic parameters, variant names and payload field type shells
- type alias shell: name and target type annotation
- trait shell: name, requirement signature shells and requirement type-reference dependency edges
- conformance shell: target type reference, trait references and declaration source context
- start shell: entry-file executable token body, excluded from dependency sorting

Parameterized generic aliases are rejected before shell creation.

## Shared declaration syntax

Declaration-shell parsers are shared with AST body-local declaration parsing.
Top-level and body-local declaration syntax should stay equivalent wherever the language allows the same shape.

Header parsing records parsed type-reference shells and dependency edges.
AST owns resolving those shells into canonical `TypeId`s.

This avoids two parsers drifting apart while still keeping semantic resolution in AST.

## Import preparation

Header parsing/import preparation builds the file-local import environment used by dependency sorting and AST.

It validates and normalizes:

- source imports
- facade re-exports
- external package imports
- aliases
- prelude/builtin reservations
- namespace records
- collision rules that can be checked structurally
- receiver-method visibility through receiver type surfaces

AST later consumes this through `ScopeContext`.
It shouldn't rebuild import bindings.

## Constants

Constants are compile-time declarations.
Header parsing records symbol-shaped references found in constant initializer tokens and resolves them far enough to create dependency edges to other constants.

Same-file constant ordering is still source-order constrained.
Same-file forward references are rejected.
Cross-file constant cycles are dependency cycles.

Constant initializer references are not body references.
They belong in the header dependency graph.

## Source-kind headers

Beandown and plain Markdown inputs synthesize ordinary private `content #String` constant declarations.

A `.bd` input contributes one private synthetic constant declaration whose initializer is a structurally built `$md` template over the original `.bd` body tokens.
AST template parsing uses that Beandown source-kind context to default nested templates with no explicit directive to `$md`: any explicit nested directive overrides the default.
A `.md` input renders raw Markdown to HTML and contributes the same private `content #String` declaration shape with a synthetic string-literal initializer.

Later dependency sorting and AST folding treat both declarations like ordinary compile-time constants.
There is no Beandown- or Markdown-specific AST node, HIR, borrow-checker or backend path.

## Header and AST boundary

Header parsing builds `ModuleSymbols`, the order-independent top-level symbol, import, export, builtin, type-alias and source-file metadata package.
Dependency sorting finalizes the sorted declaration list.
AST consumes that package directly.

AST must not rediscover top-level symbols or reconstruct top-level declaration shells from raw tokens.
If AST needs a new kind of top-level dependency, add it to headers and dependency sorting.

